uuid":"9c52b5fc-cd69-496b-ae19-b05e55139742","timestamp":"2026-04-08T19:16:18.156Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/Makefile","content":"port ?= \"8000\"\n\nautoformat:\n\tblack meerkat/ tests/ demo/\n\tisort --atomic meerkat/ tests/ demo/\n\tdocformatter --in-place --recursive meerkat tests demo\n\nlint:\n\tisort -c meerkat/ tests/ demo/\n\tblack meerkat/ tests/ demo/ --check\n\tflake8 meerkat/ tests/ demo/\n\ntest:\n\tpytest tests/\n\ntest-basic:\n\tset -e\n\tpython -c \"import meerkat as mk\"\n\tpython -c \"import meerkat.version as mversion\"\n\ntest-cov:\n\tpytest tests/ --cov=./ --cov-report=xml\n\ntest-interactive-install:\n\tset -e\n\tmk install --no-run-dev\n\ndocs:\n\tset -e\n\trm -rf docs/source/apidocs/generated\n\tpython docs/source/rst_gen.py\n\tsphinx-build -b html docs/source/ docs/build/html/\n\ndocs-check:\n\tpython docs/source/rst_gen.py\n\trm -rf docs/source/apidocs/generated\n\tsphinx-build -b html docs/source/ docs/build/html/ -W\n\nlivedocs:\n\trm -rf docs/source/apidocs/generated\n\tpython docs/source/rst_gen.py\n\tSPHINX_LIVEDOCS=true sphinx-autobuild -b html docs/source/ docs/build/html/ --port=${port}\n\nwebsite-install:\n\tcd website && npm install && cd ..\n\nwebsite:\n\tset -e\n\tmake docs -B\n\trm -rf website/static/docs\n\tmkdir -p website/static/docs\n\tcp -r docs/build/html/* website/static/docs/\n\tpython website/reroute.py\n\tcd website && npm run build\n\n\ndev:\n\tpip install black==22.12.0 isort flake8 docformatter pytest-cov sphinx-rtd-theme nbsphinx recommonmark pre-commit sphinx-panels jupyter-sphinx pydata-sphinx-theme sphinx-autobuild sphinx-toolbox sphinx-copybutton sphinx_design\n\nall: autoformat lint docs test\n","numLines":61,"startLine":1,"totalLines":61}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_3df7b32b4acd429786100ae3","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Contributing to Meerkat\n2\t\n3\tWe welcome contributions of all kinds: code, documentation, feedback and support. If\n4\t you use Meerkat in your work (blogs posts, research, company) and find it\n5\t  useful, spread the word!  \n6\t  \n7\tThis contribution borrows from and is heavily inspired by [Huggingface transformers](https://github.com/huggingface/transformers). \n8\t\n9\tIf you encounter any steps that are missing from this guide, we'd appreciate if you open an issue or a pull request to improve it.\n10\t\n11\t## How to contribute\n12\t\n13\tThere are 4 ways you can contribute:\n14\t* Issues: raising bugs, suggesting new features\n15\t* Fixes: resolving outstanding bugs\n16\t* Features: contributing new features\n17\t* Documentation: contributing documentation or examples\n18\t\n19\t## Submitting a new issue or feature request\n20\t\n21\tDo your best to follow these guidelines when submitting an issue or a feature\n22\trequest. \n23\t\n24\t**However, we actively encourage that you** \n25\t* file an incomplete issue than no issue at all\n26\t* suggest a feature that you are not sure how to implement, and even if you're unsure if it's a good idea\n27\t\n28\tIf you are unsure about something, don't hesitate to ask.\n29\t\n30\t### Bugs\n31\t\n32\tFirst, we would really appreciate it if you could **make sure the bug was not\n33\talready reported** (use the search bar on GitHub under Issues).\n34\t\n35\tIf you didn't find anything, please use the bug issue template to file a GitHub issue.  \n36\t\n37\t\n38\t### Features\n39\t\n40\tA world-class feature request addresses the following points:\n41\t\n42\t1. Motivation first:\n43\t  * Is it related to a problem/frustration with the library? If so, please explain\n44\t    why. Providing a code snippet that demonstrates the problem is best.\n45\t  * Is it related to something you would need for a project? We'd love to hear\n46\t    about it!\n47\t  * Is it something you worked on and think could benefit the community?\n48\t    Awesome! Tell us what problem it solved for you.\n49\t2. Write a *full paragraph* describing the feature;\n50\t3. Provide a **code snippet** that demonstrates its future use;\n51\t4. In case this is related to a paper, please attach a link;\n52\t5. Attach any additional information (drawings, screenshots, etc.) you think may help.\n53\t\n54\tIf your issue is well written we're already 80% of the way there by the time you\n55\tpost it.\n56\t\n57\t## Contributing (Pull Requests)\n58\t\n59\tBefore writing code, we strongly advise you to search through the existing PRs or\n60\tissues to make sure that nobody is already working on the same thing. If you are\n61\tunsure, it is always a good idea to open an issue to get some feedback.\n62\t\n63\tYou will need basic `git` proficiency to be able to contribute to\n64\t`meerkat`. `git` is not the easiest tool to use but it has the greatest\n65\tmanual. Type `git --help` in a shell and enjoy. If you prefer books, [Pro\n66\tGit](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2) is a very good reference.\n67\t\n68\tFollow these steps to start contributing:\n69\t\n70\t1. Fork the [repository](https://github.com/hazyresearch/meerkat) by\n71\t   clicking on the 'Fork' button on the repository's page. \n72\t   This creates a copy of the code under your GitHub user account.\n73\t\n74\t2. Clone your fork to your local disk, and add the base repository as a remote:\n75\t\n76\t   ```bash\n77\t   $ git clone git@github.com:<your GitHub handle>/meerkat.git\n78\t   $ cd meerkat\n79\t   $ git remote add upstream https://github.com/hazyresearch/meerkat.git\n80\t   ```\n81\t   \n82\t\n83\t3. Create a new branch off of the `main` branch to hold your development changes:\n84\t\n85\t   ```bash\n86\t   $ git fetch upstream\n87\t   $ git checkout -b a-descriptive-name-for-my-changes upstream/dev\n88\t   ```\n89\t   **Do not** work directly on the `main` branch.\n90\t\n91\t4. Meerkat manages dependencies using [`setuptools`](https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/). From the base of the `meerkat` repo, install the project in editable mode with all the extra dependencies with \n92\t\n93\t   ```bash\n94\t   $ pip install -e \".[all]\"\n95\t   ```\n96\t   If meerkat was already installed in the virtual environment, remove it with `pip uninstall meerkat-ml` before reinstalling it in editable mode with the above command.\n97\t\n98\t\n99\t5. Develop features on your branch.\n100\t\n101\t   As you work on the features, you should make sure that the test suite\n102\t   passes:\n103\t\n104\t   ```bash\n105\t   $ pytest\n106\t   ```\n107\t\n108\t   Meerkat relies on `black` and `isort` to format its source code\n109\t   consistently. After you make changes, autoformat them with:\n110\t\n111\t   ```bash\n112\t   $ make autoformat\n113\t   ```\n114\t\n115\t   Meerkat also uses `flake8` to check for coding mistakes. Quality control\n116\t    runs in CI, however you should also run the same checks with:\n117\t\n118\t   ```bash\n119\t   $ make lint\n120\t   ```\n121\t   Note: if you have a bunch of unused import warnings, you can run `autoflake --remove-all-unused-imports . -ri` to remove them. (You may need to pip install autoflake.)\n122\t\n123\t   If you're modifying documents under `docs/source`, make sure to validate that\n124\t   they can still be built. This check also runs in CI. To run a local check\n125\t   make sure you have installed the documentation builder requirements, by\n126\t   running `pip install -r docs/requirements.txt` from the root of this repository\n127\t   and then run:\n128\t\n129\t   ```bash\n130\t   $ make docs\n131\t   ```\n132\t\n133\t   You can use `pre-commit` to make sure you don't forget to format your code properly, \n134\t   the dependency should already be made available by `setuptools`.\n135\t   \n136\t   Just install `pre-commit` from the base of the `meerkat` directory with\n137\t   \n138\t   ```bash\n139\t   $ pre-commit install\n140\t   ```\n141\t\n142\t   Once you're happy with your changes, add changed files using `git add` and\n143\t   make a commit with `git commit` to record your changes locally:\n144\t\n145\t   ```bash\n146\t   $ git add modified_file.py\n147\t   $ git commit\n148\t   ```\n149\t\n150\t   Please write [good commit messages](https://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/).\n151\t\n152\t   It is a good idea to sync your copy of the code with the original\n153\t   repository regularly. This way you can quickly account for changes:\n154\t\n155\t   ```bash\n156\t   $ git fetch upstream\n157\t   $ git rebase upstream/dev\n158\t   ```\n159\t\n160\t   Push the changes to your account using:\n161\t\n162\t   ```bash\n163\t   $ git push -u origin a-descriptive-name-for-my-changes\n164\t   ```\n165\t\n166\t6. Once you are satisfied (**and the checklist below is done**), go to the\n167\t   webpage of your fork on GitHub. Click on 'Pull request' to send your changes\n168\t   to the project maintainers for review. \n169\t\n170\t   **Important**:  Ensure that the you create a pull request onto meerkat's `dev` branch. The drop down menus at the top of the \"Open a pull request page\" should look\n171\t   >base repository: **hazyresearch/meerkat**  base: **main** <- head repository: **\\<your GitHub handle\\>/meerkat**  compare: **\\<your branch name\\>** \n172\t   \n173\t\n174\t7. It's ok if maintainers ask you for changes. It happens to core contributors\n175\t   too! So everyone can see the changes in the Pull request, work in your local\n176\t   branch and push the changes to your fork. They will automatically appear in\n177\t   the pull request.\n178\t\n179\t### Checklist\n180\t\n181\t1. The title of your pull request should be a summary of its contribution;\n182\t2. If your pull request addresses an issue, please mention the issue number in\n183\t   the pull request description to make sure they are linked (and people\n184\t   consulting the issue know you are working on it);\n185\t3. To indicate a work in progress please prefix the title with `[WIP]`. These\n186\t   are useful to avoid duplicated work, and to differentiate it from PRs ready\n187\t   to be merged;\n188\t4. Make sure existing tests pass;\n189\t5. Add high-coverage tests.\n190\t6. All public methods must have informative docstrings that work nicely with sphinx.\n191\t\n192\t\n193\t### Tests\n194\t\n195\tAn extensive test suite is included to test the library behavior. \n196\tLibrary tests can be found in the \n197\t[tests folder](https://github.com/robustness-gym/meerkat/tree/main/tests).\n198\t\n199\tFrom the root of the\n200\trepository, here's how to run tests with `pytest` for the library:\n201\t\n202\t```bash\n203\t$ make test\n204\t```\n205\t\n206\tYou can specify a smaller set of tests in order to test only the feature\n207\tyou're working on.\n208\t\n209\tPer the checklist above, all PRs should include high-coverage tests. \n210\tTo produce a code coverage report, run the following `pytest`\n211\t```\n212\tpytest --cov-report term-missing,html --cov=meerkat .\n213\t```\n214\tThis will populate a directory `htmlcov` with an HTML report. \n215\tOpen `htmlcov/index.html` in a browser to view the report. \n216\t\n217\t\n218\t### Style guide\n219\t\n220\tFor documentation strings, Meerkat follows the \n221\t[google style](https://google.github.io/styleguide/pyguide.html)."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"78aa38c3-8027-4e55-ab80-47054717cfbb","uuid":"34adc3f5-64d7-4e17-ba81-64bb1a4b5d09","timestamp":"2026-04-08T19:16:18.158Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md","content":"# Contributing to Meerkat\n\nWe welcome contributions of all kinds: code, documentation, feedback and support. If\n you use Meerkat in your work (blogs posts, research, company) and find it\n  useful, spread the word!  \n  \nThis contribution borrows from and is heavily inspired by [Huggingface transformers](https://github.com/huggingface/transformers). \n\nIf you encounter any steps that are missing from this guide, we'd appreciate if you open an issue or a pull request to improve it.\n\n## How to contribute\n\nThere are 4 ways you can contribute:\n* Issues: raising bugs, suggesting new features\n* Fixes: resolving outstanding bugs\n* Features: contributing new features\n* Documentation: contributing documentation or examples\n\n## Submitting a new issue or feature request\n\nDo your best to follow these guidelines when submitting an issue or a feature\nrequest. \n\n**However, we actively encourage that you** \n* file an incomplete issue than no issue at all\n* suggest a feature that you are not sure how to implement, and even if you're unsure if it's a good idea\n\nIf you are unsure about something, don't hesitate to ask.\n\n### Bugs\n\nFirst, we would really appreciate it if you could **make sure the bug was not\nalready reported** (use the search bar on GitHub under Issues).\n\nIf you didn't find anything, please use the bug issue template to file a GitHub issue.  \n\n\n### Features\n\nA world-class feature request addresses the following points:\n\n1. Motivation first:\n  * Is it related to a problem/frustration with the library? If so, please explain\n    why. Providing a code snippet that demonstrates the problem is best.\n  * Is it related to something you would need for a project? We'd love to hear\n    about it!\n  * Is it something you worked on and think could benefit the community?\n    Awesome! Tell us what problem it solved for you.\n2. Write a *full paragraph* describing the feature;\n3. Provide a **code snippet** that demonstrates its future use;\n4. In case this is related to a paper, please attach a link;\n5. Attach any additional information (drawings, screenshots, etc.) you think may help.\n\nIf your issue is well written we're already 80% of the way there by the time you\npost it.\n\n## Contributing (Pull Requests)\n\nBefore writing code, we strongly advise you to search through the existing PRs or\nissues to make sure that nobody is already working on the same thing. If you are\nunsure, it is always a good idea to open an issue to get some feedback.\n\nYou will need basic `git` proficiency to be able to contribute to\n`meerkat`. `git` is not the easiest tool to use but it has the greatest\nmanual. Type `git --help` in a shell and enjoy. If you prefer books, [Pro\nGit](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2) is a very good reference.\n\nFollow these steps to start contributing:\n\n1. Fork the [repository](https://github.com/hazyresearch/meerkat) by\n   clicking on the 'Fork' button on the repository's page. \n   This creates a copy of the code under your GitHub user account.\n\n2. Clone your fork to your local disk, and add the base repository as a remote:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ git clone git@github.com:<your GitHub handle>/meerkat.git\n   $ cd meerkat\n   $ git remote add upstream https://github.com/hazyresearch/meerkat.git\n   ```\n   \n\n3. Create a new branch off of the `main` branch to hold your development changes:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ git fetch upstream\n   $ git checkout -b a-descriptive-name-for-my-changes upstream/dev\n   ```\n   **Do not** work directly on the `main` branch.\n\n4. Meerkat manages dependencies using [`setuptools`](https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/). From the base of the `meerkat` repo, install the project in editable mode with all the extra dependencies with \n\n   ```bash\n   $ pip install -e \".[all]\"\n   ```\n   If meerkat was already installed in the virtual environment, remove it with `pip uninstall meerkat-ml` before reinstalling it in editable mode with the above command.\n\n\n5. Develop features on your branch.\n\n   As you work on the features, you should make sure that the test suite\n   passes:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ pytest\n   ```\n\n   Meerkat relies on `black` and `isort` to format its source code\n   consistently. After you make changes, autoformat them with:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ make autoformat\n   ```\n\n   Meerkat also uses `flake8` to check for coding mistakes. Quality control\n    runs in CI, however you should also run the same checks with:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ make lint\n   ```\n   Note: if you have a bunch of unused import warnings, you can run `autoflake --remove-all-unused-imports . -ri` to remove them. (You may need to pip install autoflake.)\n\n   If you're modifying documents under `docs/source`, make sure to validate that\n   they can still be built. This check also runs in CI. To run a local check\n   make sure you have installed the documentation builder requirements, by\n   running `pip install -r docs/requirements.txt` from the root of this repository\n   and then run:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ make docs\n   ```\n\n   You can use `pre-commit` to make sure you don't forget to format your code properly, \n   the dependency should already be made available by `setuptools`.\n   \n   Just install `pre-commit` from the base of the `meerkat` directory with\n   \n   ```bash\n   $ pre-commit install\n   ```\n\n   Once you're happy with your changes, add changed files using `git add` and\n   make a commit with `git commit` to record your changes locally:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ git add modified_file.py\n   $ git commit\n   ```\n\n   Please write [good commit messages](https://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/).\n\n   It is a good idea to sync your copy of the code with the original\n   repository regularly. This way you can quickly account for changes:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ git fetch upstream\n   $ git rebase upstream/dev\n   ```\n\n   Push the changes to your account using:\n\n   ```bash\n   $ git push -u origin a-descriptive-name-for-my-changes\n   ```\n\n6. Once you are satisfied (**and the checklist below is done**), go to the\n   webpage of your fork on GitHub. Click on 'Pull request' to send your changes\n   to the project maintainers for review. \n\n   **Important**:  Ensure that the you create a pull request onto meerkat's `dev` branch. The drop down menus at the top of the \"Open a pull request page\" should look\n   >base repository: **hazyresearch/meerkat**  base: **main** <- head repository: **\\<your GitHub handle\\>/meerkat**  compare: **\\<your branch name\\>** \n   \n\n7. It's ok if maintainers ask you for changes. It happens to core contributors\n   too! So everyone can see the changes in the Pull request, work in your local\n   branch and push the changes to your fork. They will automatically appear in\n   the pull request.\n\n### Checklist\n\n1. The title of your pull request should be a summary of its contribution;\n2. If your pull request addresses an issue, please mention the issue number in\n   the pull request description to make sure they are linked (and people\n   consulting the issue know you are working on it);\n3. To indicate a work in progress please prefix the title with `[WIP]`. These\n   are useful to avoid duplicated work, and to differentiate it from PRs ready\n   to be merged;\n4. Make sure existing tests pass;\n5. Add high-coverage tests.\n6. All public methods must have informative docstrings that work nicely with sphinx.\n\n\n### Tests\n\nAn extensive test suite is included to test the library behavior. \nLibrary tests can be found in the \n[tests folder](https://github.com/robustness-gym/meerkat/tree/main/tests).\n\nFrom the root of the\nrepository, here's how to run tests with `pytest` for the library:\n\n```bash\n$ make test\n```\n\nYou can specify a smaller set of tests in order to test only the feature\nyou're working on.\n\nPer the checklist above, all PRs should include high-coverage tests. \nTo produce a code coverage report, run the following `pytest`\n```\npytest --cov-report term-missing,html --cov=meerkat .\n```\nThis will populate a directory `htmlcov` with an HTML report. \nOpen `htmlcov/index.html` in a browser to view the report. \n\n\n### Style guide\n\nFor documentation strings, Meerkat follows the \n[google style](https://google.github.io/styleguide/pyguide.html).","numLines":221,"startLine":1,"totalLines":221}}}
